               <p>JAMES STEDMAN. I have a house in <placeName id="t18280410-147-crimeloc794">St. Luke's</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-147-crimeloc794" type="placeName" value="St. Luke's"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-147-crimeloc794" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-147-off792 t18280410-147-crimeloc794"></join> - it was empty on the 21st of March; these doors were fixed in it; I have compared them - they fit exactly.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-147-person890">
                  ROBERT 
                  LOCK
               <interp inst="t18280410-147-person890" type="surname" value="LOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-147-person890" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-147-person890" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. On the morning of the 21st of March I saw the prisoner in a stone passage in Chequer-alley, offering these four doors for sale; that was two or three hundred yards from the house they were taken from; he said a man gave them to him - he said he should not know the man, but that he had a fustian coat on, and white stockings.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. A gentleman brought them to me, and said, "Will you just look after these till I go and get a customer," and he said he would give me a shilling.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280410-147-verdict795" type="verdictDescription">
